    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm, I'm hesitant to introduce a new keyword in the name scheme.</p>",
        "id": 480586203,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1730788456
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about following <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=add_sub_cancel_left#doc\">docs#add_sub_cancel_left</a> ?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">or_and_cancel_left</span>\n<span class=\"n\">or_and_cancel_right</span>\n<span class=\"n\">and_or_cancel_left</span>\n<span class=\"n\">and_or_cancel_right</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 480667069,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1730796007
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But there's no cancellation, only absorption</p>",
        "id": 480668671,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1730796546
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">or_and_absorbs_right</span>\n<span class=\"n\">or_and_absorbs_left</span>\n<span class=\"n\">and_or_absorbs_right</span>\n<span class=\"n\">and_or_absorbs_left</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 480668909,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1730796659
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think <code>absorbs</code> is already used in this sense in Mathlib (as far as I can tell, it's mostly used for topological vector spaces, in a rather precise sense), so I'd rather avoid introducing new terminology that users couldn't guess. <code>cancel</code> would be more standard in this respect.</p>",
        "id": 480671361,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1730797456
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another possibility is <code>or_and_iff_self_left</code>, <code>or_and_iff_self_right</code>, <code>and_or_iff_self_left</code> and <code>and_or_iff_self_right</code>.</p>",
        "id": 480671700,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1730797579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And what about these lemmas?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">or_and_left_self_left</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">or_and_left_self_right</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">and_or_right_self_left</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">and_or_right_self_right</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 480674432,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1730798477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110050\">Sébastien Gouëzel</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/naming.20some.20lemmas.20about.20Prop/near/480671361\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I don't think <code>absorbs</code> is already used in this sense in Mathlib (as far as I can tell, it's mostly used for topological vector spaces, in a rather precise sense), so I'd rather avoid introducing new terminology that users couldn't guess.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Indeed, I am suggesting we introduce a new naming convention for lemmas of a new kind. We successfully similarly introduced <code>anticomm</code>, <code>rotate</code> and <code>antidistrib</code> in the past</p>",
